  "title": "Reverse transcriptase and Cell Function",
  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><p class=\"passage_para\">Retroviruses such as <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H I V\"><math alttext=\"H I V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>HIV</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and hepatitis&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>B</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> virus use <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R N A\"><math alttext=\"R N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>RNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> as their genetic material rather than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. In addition, they contain molecules of reverse transcriptase, an enzyme that uses an <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R N A\"><math alttext=\"R N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>RNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>&nbsp;template to synthesize complementary&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following best predicts what will happen when a normal cell is exposed to a retrovirus?</p>\n",
    "answer": "i3",
    "choices": [
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The reverse transcriptase will cut the host&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> into fragments, destroying the host cell.</p>",
        "value": "i1"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The reverse transcriptase will insert the viral&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R N A\"><math alttext=\"R N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>RNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> into the host’s genome so it can be transcribed and translated.</p>",
        "value": "i2"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The reverse transcriptase will produce <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from the viral&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R N A\"><math alttext=\"R N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>RNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, which can be incorporated into the host’s genome and then transcribed and translated.</p>",
        "value": "i3"
      },
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The reverse transcriptase will force the host ribosomes to translate the viral&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R N A\"><math alttext=\"R N A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>RNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> prior to polypeptide assembly.</p>",
        "value": "i4"
      }
    ]
  },
